ly analyzing key turning points and institutions in recent history. He presents a sociology of human interactions that lead from small to large: dissent around the old Soviet bloc; life on the streets in Warsaw, Prague, and Bucharest in 1989; the network of terror that spawned 9/11; and the religious and Internet mobilizations that transformed the 2004 presidential election, to name a few. In such pivotal moments, he masterfully shows, political autonomy can be generated, presenting alternatives to the big politics of the global stage and the dominant narratives of terrorism, antiterrorism, and globalization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aPolitical sociology. 0aPolitics and culture. 0aSocial interactionxPolitical aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  asocial change, revolution, grassroots, politics, protest, resistance, history, 2004 election, mobilization, internet, 9/11, terrorism, state violence, fear, bucharest, prague, warsaw, soviet bloc, dissent, dialogue, power, nonfiction, speech, rhetoric, redeem the vote, moveon, sociology, political science, autonomy, authority, globalization, antiterrorism, interaction, narrative, religion, church, democracy, self, media, cell phones, communication, digital.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226301112423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226301112/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles